  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Inscribed on a Monk's Dwelling
  author: Byeon Gyeryangb
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Worldly visitors come to pay homage to the Buddha,
    while the venerable monk sits chanting sutras.
    Daylight lamps darken the ancient walls with their smoke,
    and the gnarled cypress echoes through the empty courtyard.
    The pagoda rises in three white tiers,
    the mountains encircle in layers of green on all sides.
    In the meditation hall, there is nothing left to do—
    all day long I lean against the wind-swept railing.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The cypress (檜) is a traditional symbol of longevity and resilience in East Asian poetry.
  - key: ''
    value: The three-tiered pagoda is a common architectural feature in Buddhist temples, representing the three realms or aspects of Buddhist cosmology.
  - key: ''
    value: The final couplet suggests a state of spiritual emptiness and peace, where the speaker finds contentment in simple observation and receptiveness.
